kford, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Icklingham, Suffolk, England":"Icklingham, Suffolk, England","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Gedding","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German and Dutch: habitational name from any of several farms so named (in Lower Saxony or in the province of Drenthe), once belonging to a certain <i>Gerd</i> and his kin. The personal name <i>Gerd</i> is a shortened form of   Gerhardt  . Compare   Gardin  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Gardin","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Homero, Ramonda, Ruben.  Italian Mario, Orlando.","Americanized form of German   Gerding  . It is concentrated in NC.","Italian (Veneto): from a pet form of <i>Gardo</i>, a short form of various personal names such as <i>Edgardo</i> and <i>Ildegardo</i>."]},{"name":"Gerhardt","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Armin, Wilhelm, Bernhard, Dieter, Erwin, Gerda, Gerhardt, Heinrich, Heinz, Horst.","German: from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>gēr</i>, <i>gār</i> ‘spear’ + <i>hard</i> ‘hardy, brave, strong’. Compare   Garhart  ,   Gearhart  , and   Gearheart  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Gedding was born in 1400, in Suffolk, England, United Kingdom, his father, William Gedding, was 32 and his mother, Myrabe